Purpose of application

So basically we have an app where we researched about dead people and how they lived their lives, when did they die, and also what impact did they have in that community/ country they were living in. As said all that, the purpose for my app is to display the age that matches with the individual you are looking for. Most of the people that will be using my app is mostly going to be students, because they want to find out more about the history of that particular individual.

Design considerations

![](data:image/png;base64,)

2 Design Considerations

\- The Create button is what the user will use when they insert a certain age, basically when they click on this button, it will show the information about the age they have entered.

\- The Cancel button will be used when the user wants to clear the previous age and enter a new age to find out another persons information.

\- The TEXTDisplay is where all the information about the dead person will be displayed, this will also display the text “ invalid” age if the user has entered a age that doesn’t correspond with the age in the code.

\- And lastly the PLAINTEXT, this is where the user will enter all the ages that are in the code.

Content prioritization

So my program is basically simple, because I only entered/ used important interfaces and content. Basically just putting 2 buttons, a text view for the result, and the plain text. And lastly, the color of my background is peach, because light colors are beautiful and I wanted my application to also look nice, hence I chose the light color peach.

LEGIBLE TEXT CONTENT

This question is based on font and my answer is that I did use the font that will be visible to the user or anybody. So for both the buttons, my font size was 34sp, written in white, this was because I wanted the user to know very well which button they are pressing. The font size for my plain text where the user will enter the age is 24sp, which is written in black, this is because black is visible enough to light colors, especially with the font size I used. And my text view result is 14sp, I designed it this way, because its obvious its where the output will go, so the result text must not be that visible and block some of the output. Lastly my last text view which shows the name of the application is in 24sp, so the user can know what they are working on or even what the application is for.

Make interface elements clearly visible

Yes all the components on the screen are clearly visible, because each component is in different color, meaning that it will be easier for the user to tell the difference between all the components. And lastly, the components are not mixed/ to close to each other, because I adjusted the constraints for every component on my design.

Hand position controls

All the buttons I have inserted, which are 2 are not very apart from each other, but there is still enough space in between, so that when the user is done with the other button, they can just go to the other button without using the mouse a lot.

IMAGES

So my image about history was put in the middle and enlarged, because I wanted to make space for the other components that I had to enter. And the reason why I chose the picture I chose, it is because everything in that picture is part of history, from the map looking like it survived world war 2 or was used in world war 2, to the ancient compass, that was used back in the day, when a person was lost.

3 GitHub and GitHub Actions

1\. Create a New GitHub Repository:

Go to the GitHub website (<https://github.com/>) and sign in to your account.

Click on the "+" icon in the top right corner and select "New repository".

Give your repository a name (ST10451243, Bongani Dlamini), Name :MyFinalHistoryApp and choose public.

Click on the "Create repository" button.

2\. Initialise the Repository with a README File:

After creating the repository, you'll see an option to "Initialize this repository with a README". Check this option to create a README file.

Click on the "Create repository" button to finalize the creation of the repository.

3\. Commit and Push Your Project Files to the GitHub Repository:

In Android Studio, go to VCS (Version Control System) -> Import into Version Control -> Share Project on GitHub.

Log in to your GitHub account if prompted, and select the repository you created earlier.

Click on the "Share" button to push your project files to the GitHub repository.

4\. Regularly Commit and Push Your Code as You Make Progress:

After the initial push, continue making changes to your project in Android Studio.

Whenever you make significant progress or changes, commit your changes locally in Android Studio using VCS -> Commit Changes.

Once committed, push your changes to the GitHub repository using VCS -> Git -> Push.

**Testing and Automated Testing**:

1\. Conduct Manual Testing:

Manually test your app to ensure it functions seamlessly and offers an enjoyable educational experience for learners.

To test various features and user interactions do the following:

1\. Create a New Test Class:

In your Android project, navigate to the tests directory (or create it if it doesn't exist).

Create a new Kotlin file for your test class. Name it appropriately to indicate what component or functionality you are testing.

2\. Write Test Methods:

Inside the test class, write test methods like the example below.

3\. Use assertions to verify the expected behaviour of your code.

4\. Run the Tests:

Run the tests using the testing framework's tools provided by Android Studio or through the command line.

Sample of a test class using JUnit:

import org.junit.Assert.\*

import org.junit.Test

class MyUnitTest {

@Test

// Test case for a when statement

2\. GitHub Actions for Automated Testing:

Set up GitHub Actions to automatically run tests and build your code whenever changes are pushed to the repository.

Create a GitHub Actions workflow (.github/workflows/tests.yml) to run tests automatically on every push:

Create a .github/workflows directory in your project repository.

Inside this directory, create YAML files defining your GitHub Actions workflows for testing and building.

**Sample GitHub Actions Workflow for Testing (tests.yml):**

name: Run Tests

on: \[push\]

jobs:

test:

runs-on: ubuntu-latest

steps:

\- name: Set up JDK

uses: actions/setup-java@v2

with:

distribution: 'adopt'

java-version: '11'

\- name: Check out code

uses: actions/checkout@v2

\- name: Build and test

run: ./gradlew test

Set Up Automated Build:

Create a GitHub Actions workflow (.github/workflows/build.yml) to build the APK automatically on every push.

**Sample GitHub Actions Workflow for Building (build.yml):**

name: Build APK

on: \[push\]

jobs:

build:

runs-on: ubuntu-latest

steps:

\- name: Set up JDK

uses: actions/setup-java@v2

with:

distribution: 'adopt'

java-version: '11'

\- name: Check out code

uses: actions/checkout@v2

\- name: Build APK

run: ./gradlew assembleDebug

Test your workflows by pushing changes to your repository and observing the actions running in the "Actions" tab on GitHub.
